  "prompt": "How can Sanskrit, the so-called mother of all languages, be a dead language today?",
  "response": "There is a common misconception that Sanskrit is a \"dead language.\" In reality, Sanskrit is more accurately categorized as a \"classical language.\" Similar to Latin or Ancient Greek, Sanskrit\u2019s use as a spoken vernacular has declined significantly over the centuries, but it remains very much alive in several key areas:\n\n1. **Religious and Ritualistic Use**: Sanskrit continues to be used in Hindu religious practices, rituals, and ceremonies. Many mantras and hymns are recited in Sanskrit, and numerous religious texts are written in the language.\n\n2. **Scholarly and Literary Activity**: Sanskrit is still studied and researched extensively by linguists, historians, and scholars of ancient Indian literature and philosophy. There is a substantial corpus of ancient texts in Sanskrit, including Vedas, Upanishads, epics like the Mahabharata and Ramayana, and various treatises on philosophy, science, medicine, and the arts.\n\n3. **Pedagogical and Revival Efforts**: Efforts to revive and promote Sanskrit are ongoing. Various educational institutions and programs around the world teach Sanskrit, and some communities, particularly in India, actively work to keep the language in use.\n\n4. **Modern Adaptations**: Sanskrit has found applications in the modern world, such as computer programming languages and artificial intelligence, due to its precise and structured nature.\n\nThe term \"dead language\" typically refers to a language that no longer has any native speakers and is not used for practical communication. While Sanskrit may not be the native tongue of any community today, it continues to thrive in specific contexts, reflecting its enduring cultural and intellectual significance.",
